# ==============================================================================
# FRONTEND ENVIRONMENT CONFIGURATION
# ==============================================================================
#
# NOTE: As of the configuration consolidation, the Deep Agent AGI frontend
# now reads ALL environment variables from the ROOT .env file.
#
# You DO NOT need to create a frontend/.env.local file anymore.
#
# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
# HOW FRONTEND CONFIGURATION WORKS
# ==============================================================================
#
# Next.js automatically reads environment variables from the following files
# in order of precedence (highest to lowest):
#
# 1. .env.local (root directory)          - Local overrides (gitignored)
# 2. .env.development / .env.production   - Environment-specific
# 3. .env (root directory)                - Default configuration
#
# All NEXT_PUBLIC_* variables defined in the root .env file are:
# - Available on the server (Node.js)
# - Embedded in the browser bundle at BUILD TIME
# - Accessible via process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_* in React components
#
# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
# REQUIRED FRONTEND VARIABLES (MUST BE IN ROOT .ENV)
# ==============================================================================
#
# These variables MUST be defined in the root .env file for the frontend to work:
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:8000
#   - Backend API base URL
#   - Used for API calls and WebSocket connections
#   - DEFAULT: http://localhost:8000
#   - PRODUCTION: Update with your actual backend domain
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_WS_URL=ws://localhost:8000 (optional)
#   - WebSocket URL for streaming
#   - If not set, inferred from NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL
#   - Only set if WebSocket is on different URL than API
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_ENV=development (optional)
#   - Environment identifier for frontend
#   - DEFAULT: Inferred from NODE_ENV
#   - OPTIONS: development, staging, production
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_REASONING_UI=true (optional)
#   - Show reasoning effort indicators in UI
#   - DEFAULT: true
#   - PRODUCTION: Set to false to hide internal reasoning details
#
# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
# OPTIONAL FRONTEND VARIABLES (PHASE 1 & 2)
# ==============================================================================
#
# These variables are planned for future phases. They should be added to
# the root .env file when implementing the corresponding features:
#
# PHASE 1 - Authentication & Monitoring:
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_LANGSMITH_API_KEY=
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_LANGSMITH_PROJECT=deep-agent-agi-frontend
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN=
#
# PHASE 1 - Feature Flags:
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_HITL=true
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_STREAMING=true
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_MEMORY_SYSTEM=false
#
# PHASE 2 - Agent Configuration:
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_AGENT_NAME=deepAgent
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_RESEARCH_MODE=false
#
# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
# SERVER-ONLY VARIABLES (NOT EXPOSED TO BROWSER)
# ==============================================================================
#
# These variables are available on the Next.js server but NOT in the browser
# (they don't have the NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix). Add them to root .env if needed:
#
# Server-Side API Integration:
#   ALLOWED_ORIGINS=http://localhost:3000,http://localhost:3001
#     - CSRF protection for API routes
#
# Rate Limiting (Upstash Redis) - OPTIONAL:
#   UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL=
#   UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN=
#     - Server-side rate limiting for API routes
#     - Phase 2 feature
#
# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
# LOCAL DEVELOPMENT OVERRIDES (OPTIONAL)
# ==============================================================================
#
# If you need to override specific frontend settings locally without modifying
# the root .env file, you can create a root .env.local file (gitignored):
#
# Example root .env.local (for local dev overrides):
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://my-custom-backend:8000
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_DEBUG=true
#   NODE_ENV=development
#
# This file will take precedence over root .env but will NOT be committed to git.
#
# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
# MIGRATION NOTES (FOR DEVELOPERS)
# ==============================================================================
#
# If you previously had a frontend/.env.local file, it has been removed as part
# of the configuration consolidation.
#
# To migrate your local settings:
# 1. Copy the settings from your old frontend/.env.local
# 2. Add them to the root .env file (for permanent settings)
#    OR
#    Add them to a root .env.local file (for local overrides only)
#
# All frontend settings are now managed from the project root.
#
# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
# TESTING CONFIGURATION
# ==============================================================================
#
# For testing, the frontend uses frontend/.env.test which is still maintained
# separately for test-specific configuration:
#
# - frontend/.env.test contains test fixtures and mock data settings
# - Used by Jest and Playwright for automated testing
# - Kept separate from root .env to isolate test configuration
#
# This file is committed to version control as it contains no secrets.
#
# ==============================================================================

# ==============================================================================
# QUICK START FOR NEW DEVELOPERS
# ==============================================================================
#
# 1. Copy root .env.example to root .env:
#    $ cp .env.example .env
#
# 2. Fill in your API keys in root .env:
#    - OPENAI_API_KEY
#    - PERPLEXITY_API_KEY (optional)
#    - LANGSMITH_API_KEY (optional)
#
# 3. Verify frontend variables are set in root .env:
#    - NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:8000
#    - NEXT_PUBLIC_WS_URL=ws://localhost:8000
#
# 4. Start the development servers:
#    $ ./scripts/start-all.sh
#
# 5. Frontend will automatically read configuration from root .env
#
# NO frontend-specific .env file is needed!
#
# ==============================================================================
